          <h2 class="mt-5">How Writle Enhances Your Writing</h2>

          <h3 class="mt-5">Creating a Project</h3>
          <p>Your journey on Writle begins with a project. Each project is a dedicated space for a specific story or piece of writing you're working on. It's where your creativity takes shape and transforms into text.</p>

          <h3 class="mt-5">Documents & Collections</h3>
          <p>Documents:
            <br>The backbone of your project, documents are where your main text lives. This is where you write your chapters, scenes, or articles. Documents are designed to be dynamic, allowing for text highlighting that links directly to your notes.
          </p>
          <p>Collections:
            <br>These are repositories for your entries, serving as notes that directly relate to your text. Collections help you organize thoughts, character bios, research, and any other supplementary information that supports your document. When a piece of text in your document is associated with an entry in a collection, Writle provides a seamless way to view those notes.
          </p>
          <p>Highlighting and Cross-Referencing:
            <br>Writle's powerful feature is the ability to highlight specific texts within your documents and associate them with entries in your collections. For example, highlighting a character's name in your document allows you to quickly access a pop-up of notes related to that character—stored in your collections. This instant access to associated notes helps you maintain narrative consistency and deepen your story's complexity without disrupting your writing flow.
          </p>





          <h2 class="mt-5">Why Choose Writle?</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Centralize your writing projects and supporting notes in one accessible place.</li>
